[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, you\'ve been seeing stuff that looks like this, but you don\'t know how to search [music] for it. So, you\'re coming up with stuff that looks super random or just nowhere close. Well, all is well because I\'m going to give you 10 nostalgic design names, and all 10 of these styles in the video come from a'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'specific window of time, roughly between the \'50s and the early 2000s. [music] Some of them defined entire industries, and some of them are circling back to now in a big way, so get excited. All of them have a visual language specific'

[00:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'enough that you could apply it to a project today, and people will still understand it. So, let\'s get started. Transparent tech, which you might also call translucent core or maybe techno color, comes from the \'90s and early'

[00:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '2000s consumer electronics. So, remember the Game Boy Color, the transparent color iMacs, the see-through Tamagotchis. The defining feature is obviously translucent or near clear plastic with colors like lime green,'

[00:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'purple, icy blue, and orange, where you can see the internal components. That was the whole point. Now, what\'s awesome is we\'re starting to see some of this come back, not only in the UI systems on your computer, but as actual products as well, which is super cool. For your'

[01:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'design projects, this translates into tech brands, [music] product packaging for electronics, maybe app icon designs. And if you\'re into print on demand, maybe create some designs with that \'90s nostalgic look and feel, or maybe even references to those \'90s style designs.'

[01:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Memphis design is a graphic movement from the early 1980s. Now, it was created by a design collective called the Memphis Group, based in Milan. The visual style is defined by flat'

[01:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'geometric shapes like triangles, zigzags, dots, other squiggles, and they\'re all layered together without any gradients or shadows. So, the palette mixes primary colors like red, yellow, and blue with secondary colors like pink, teal, and acid green, almost'

[01:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'always with black outlines. You\'ll also notice that Memphis compositions are intentionally busy. So, the shapes are filling up the entire space. There\'s not a noticeable hierarchy, and it\'s pretty chaotic. The typography sometimes sits'

[01:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'just on top of all of that pattern instead of being integrated in it. I think this style works pretty well for event branding, poster designs, apparel graphics, and any designs aimed at audiences drawn to 80s nostalgia. It\'s also a strong fit for any brand that'

[02:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'needs to feel bold with high energy without having to go straight into synthwave, which we\'ll talk about later. All right, the third design style I am calling Akira core, which pulls from 80s and 90s Japanese cyberpunk. Which, by'

[02:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the way, that\'s another search term you can use in Pinterest. And the influence is directly related to those 80s anime, manga, and the street level visual culture of cities like Tokyo. The palette uses near black or dark colored'

[02:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'backgrounds with bright reds, pinks, blues, and sharp yellows that cut through. Japanese typography will probably come up in your searches with both the kanji and the katakana, and they appear frequently as a design'

[02:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'element. And sometimes both the Japanese and English will be paired together or even on top of each other. You\'ll also notice some cinematic framing here with motion lines heavy contrast, dark environments, bright light. And there\'s a visual tension usually between'

[02:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'technology and humanity. The style is broader than any single film series. I think Akira, Ghost in the Shell, followed by Cowboy Bebop are great examples of this, all of which I think are incredible shows. Now, this style'

[03:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'works well for apparel graphics, music and event branding, gaming adjacent content, and any editorial illustrations because it has that cinematic skyline background to it. Album covers also come to mind as some projects that would work'

[03:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'well since the framing can lend itself to a smaller format. 90s editorial is the visual language of print advertising in magazines roughly from 1988 to 1999. The defining feature here is large'

[03:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'amounts of white space around a single product cutout. Clean typographic hierarchy with very short copy that carries a whole message. And the palettes are usually going to be black, white, maybe one or two colors. You\'ll notice that the typography does a lot of'

[03:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the heavy lifting. There\'s going to be some sort of condensed sans serif or a strong serif at scale with headlines that assume that the reader shouldn\'t need to really know anything else. It\'s pretty much explained. So, thanks Sony, Reebok, and old Braun ads. They\'re good'

[03:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'references for this. The style translates into brand identity systems, tech branding, editorial layouts, and it really just suits any project where you want to provide a message with confidence. All right, back to synthwave'

[04:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'specifically, neon synthwave rooted in 1980s retrofuturism, another search term for you. The palette here is consistent across a lot of this. So, deep purple black backgrounds, neon pink, teal, warm'

[04:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'gradients, and chrome or neon text effects with strong highlight lines. There are also a lot of perspective grid floors and palm tree silhouettes that you\'re going to see in these designs. You\'ll also notice that the style'

[04:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'features a lot of glow, lens effects, layered gradients, and this all gives it a sense of depth as opposed to something flat or 2D. Synthwave works well for music branding, event posters, gaming content, apparel. Now, because of the'

[04:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'age of this style and the appreciation for it, there\'s actually a large and engaged audience already fluent in this design language, and so it could really work to your advantage for some future projects. 8-bit pixel art is a visual style built directly on the hardware'

[05:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'constraints of early video game consoles. The characters, objects, and environments were made on a visible pixel grid using a fixed number of flat colors. Now, this was typically between 4 and 16. There weren\'t gradients, and'

[05:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'there [music] weren\'t any details smaller than a single block. So, think Space Invaders, Pac-Man, any original Nintendo titles that you can use as source material. You\'ll notice that the color palettes are specific and limited. [music] So, think of the green of the'

[05:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Game Boy color screen, the yellow of Pac-Man, the exact red of Mario\'s hat. It\'s pretty much all RGB, and it wasn\'t really an aesthetic choice. The developers were just working with what they had. But now, it\'s a strong visual cue for the style. This style works for'

[05:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'gaming brands, retro-themed apparel, POD designs that are for gaming audiences, and it also works as mascot or icon design when you use it tastefully and for a brand that just wants to reference'

[05:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'early digital culture. Airbrush illustration seemed like the dominant commercial art style from the 1970s through the 1980s. This technique was exactly what it sounds like, spraying paint through a pressurized tool, which'

[06:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'produces extremely smooth gradients, hyperrealistic surface sheen, and glossy three-dimensional quality. I mean, it does if you know how to do it. In the reference images you\'re seeing here,'

[06:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it\'s applied to product illustrations like drinks, sneakers, tech products, packaging, and it\'s almost like a photo was taken and effects were put on top, but this was all done with paint. Interestingly, a similar process was used in older movies like Star Wars for'

[06:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'backdrops and skylines where CGI just wasn\'t around. Now, it wasn\'t exactly airbrush, but the point here is that there were some incredible artists. There still are incredible artists creating realistic and tangible things the viewer would never second-guess.'

[06:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'You\'ll also notice that objects in this style are almost always placed against a darker or gradient background with strong highlights and shadows used to show the material of a surface as a light reflection. Now, for design'

[06:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'projects, this works well for product packaging, poster design, any brand that wants to lean into that \'80s commercial style. It\'s also great for anyone working in retro branding because this style probably translates better than'

[07:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'many others for that period. All right, let\'s go back a little further in time for pop art, a visual movement from the 1950s and \'60s, which took imagery from commercial culture, comic books, advertising, things like that, and'

[07:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'they\'re using it as subject matter for graphic design. The visual markers are this Benday dot, a halftone dot pattern from cheap color printing. There\'s going to be black outlines, flat primary fills, high contrast. Roy Lichtenstein and Andy Warhol are the most referenced'

[07:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'figures here if you would like to read up about the history. Now, what we\'re showing you here is probably a little bit more vibrant and clean. We\'re pulling these from Pinterest and the halftones here and other color methods are kind of intentionally done as'

[07:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'opposed to a mistake or an accident. You\'ll also notice that the text is used as visual elements at scale. So, you\'re going to have automonopia like a pow or a boom, a bang. You\'re also going to have text inside speech bubbles like a'

[07:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'comic book or you might have them as decorative headlines. And I like the style because it kind of flattens everything to the same visual weight. Now, pop art translates well into poster designs, apparel graphics, maybe some packaging that needs to feel really bold'

[08:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'or immediate, or maybe even campaign branding where you want it to be very loud and very noticeable. Riso graph is a print style that comes from a specific machine, the Riso duplicator, which is a'

[08:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Japanese stencil printer developed in the \'80s. The visual characteristics come directly from how this printer works. Ink was applied one color at a time, layers overlap, they misregister'

[08:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'slightly, and they create a visible offset between colors. The ink is also porous, it\'s kind of slightly grainy, and it gives it that texture which is distinct from any other print process. Now, we have a video or two already on the Riso print and the Riso graph style'

[08:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'here on the channel. So, if you\'re into that, we\'re also showing you how to make it in Kittle. So, make sure you check that out. You might also notice that Riso work uses a maximum of two to four colors and the combination tends towards unexpected pairings. So, you\'re going to'

[09:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'have fluorescent pink, teal, maybe yellow or navy, and the colors have a slightly faded washed quality because the inks aren\'t fully opaque. Now, this style works well for event posters, music packaging, zines, greeting cards,'

[09:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'any brand that wants to communicate an indie or hand-crafted printed quality. It\'s also one of the most effective styles for digital designs that are meant to look like they were physically printed because not everybody has the'

[09:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'money to go out and buy one of these printers, but you can do it really easily. And again, we have tutorials on how to do this in Kittle. If you want to try it out right now, the link is in the description. All right, lastly, we\'re going to talk about functional'

[09:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'utilitarian design, but there are two specific names or titles worth knowing. The first is a name, and that is Dieter Rams, the lead designer at Braun from the \'50s through the \'80s, and his design principles focused entirely on'

[09:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'function, honesty, and removing everything that\'s not necessary in a composition. The second name or title you might have heard of is the hit series Severance. And Severance design is what most people are probably going'

[10:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to search and find a lot of on Pinterest, myself included. And we\'re referencing the visual identity of that show, and it applies to a lot of those same principles from Rams to corporate environments, printed materials, and graphic systems. You\'ll notice strict'

[10:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'grid systems, neutral sans serif typography that\'s set in high contrast, a palette of black, white, gray, and maybe one restrained accent color. So, probably blue or pink or a green that\'s a lot more muted. And for your layouts,'

[10:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you have every element, every piece of type placed at the right size and the right position that it needs to be for that job. Nothing was really added for decoration, and if a shape is there or appears, it\'s doing something or it has'

[10:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a purpose. Now, this style works really well for tech and product branding, corporate identity systems, packaging that needs to communicate something very precise, and really any brand that wants to position itself as a very highly'

[10:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'considered or intelligent option in its category. All right, there were 10 nostalgic names that you can now go search along with some other search terms. We used Pinterest very heavily for this one, and I\'m sure you can find'

[11:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'some other [music] options on just Google or on Instagram. And if you have one in mind that we didn\'t mention, make sure you go down and comment down in the comments so we can check it out and maybe make a [music] future video about it. Again, a lot of these styles we have'

[11:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in Kiddo, whether it\'s elements or fonts or templates that are already ready to go for you. So, make sure you sign up to check those out. The link is down in the description. And of course, while you\'re there, make sure you subscribe so you'

[11:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'don\'t miss videos just like this one. Thank you so much for watching and we will see you in the next video. &gt;&gt; [music]'
